Create Function: Clean_Text_Advanced¶

Setting up the stop words list and the lemmatizer so I can filter out common words and reduce words to their base form later. Then, I define a function called clean_text_advanced that handles the main cleaning tasks. This function expands contractions like “don’t” to “do not,” removes any HTML tags and non-letter characters, converts the text to lowercase, tokenizes it into individual words, removes stop words, and lemmatizes each word. Finally, it joins the cleaned words back into a single string to get a cleaned version of each review.

In [32]:
#setting stop words and lemmatizer
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

#defining function for expanding contractions, cleaning text, removing stopwords, and lemmatizing
def clean_text_advanced(text):
    text = contractions.fix(text)
    text = re.sub(r'<.*?>', '', text)
    text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z ]', '', text)
    text = text.lower()
    words = word_tokenize(text)
    words = [lemmatizer.lemmatize(w) for w in words if w not in stop_words]
    return ' '.join(words)

Feature Engineering¶

Text is converted into numerical representations so models can learn. For this step, we use:

  • TF-IDF for word frequency and importance
  • POS tagging for syntactic context

Numerical representation is needed to train classifiers. TF-IDF is fast and effective (especially when data is sparse), then POS tagging can enrich context. Additionally, logistic regression (which we will use later) performs well on TF-IDF features in sentiment tasks and POS-based features can enhance signal for sentiment polarity.

In [34]:
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from nltk import pos_tag, word_tokenize
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
import scipy

# Encode binary labels (1 = positive, 0 = negative)
df['label'] = df['sentiment'].map({'positive': 1, 'negative': 0})

# TF-IDF vectorization
tfidf_vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=5000, ngram_range=(1, 2))
X_tfidf = tfidf_vectorizer.fit_transform(df['cleaned_review'])

# POS tagging to count adjectives and adverbs
def count_pos_tags(text):
  tags = [tag for word, tag in pos_tag(word_tokenize(text))]
  return tags.count('JJ') + tags.count('RB')

df['pos_count'] = df['cleaned_review'].apply(count_pos_tags)

# Normalize and combine TF-IDF and POS features
pos_scaled = MinMaxScaler().fit_transform(df[['pos_count']])
X_final = scipy.sparse.hstack((X_tfidf, pos_scaled))
y = df['label']

Baseline Modeling (Logistic Regression and GridSearchCV)¶

A baseline model is trained using logistic regression and hyperparameters are tuned for best performance. This model is fast and performs well on high-dimensional sparse data like TF-IDF matrices but is ideal for text classification. GridSearchCV is used to find the optimal C value which increases generalization while reducing overfitting. A confusion matrix, classification report, and SHAP explainability are also provided to assess model performance and feature importance.

In [42]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix, roc_curve, auc, RocCurveDisplay
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import shap

# Train test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_final, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42, stratify=y)

# Grid search over regularization parameter
param_grid = {'C': [0.1, 1, 10]}
grid = GridSearchCV(LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000), param_grid, cv=5, scoring='f1')
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Evaluate
y_pred = grid.predict(X_test)
print("Best Parameters:", grid.best_params_)
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred, target_names=["Negative", "Positive"]))

# Confusion Matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Purples', xticklabels=["Negative", "Positive"], yticklabels=["Negative", "Positive"])
plt.title("Confusion Matrix - Logistic Regression")
plt.xlabel("Predicted")
plt.ylabel("Actual")
plt.show()

# ROC Curve
y_prob_lr = grid.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

fpr_lr, tpr_lr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob_lr)
roc_auc_lr = auc(fpr_lr, tpr_lr)

plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
plt.plot(fpr_lr, tpr_lr, label=f"Logistic Regression (AUC = {roc_auc_lr:.2f})", color='darkorange')
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', label='Random Guess')
plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
plt.title("ROC Curve - Logistic Regression")
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# SHAP Explainability
explainer = shap.Explainer(grid.best_estimator_, X_train)
shap_values = explainer(X_test[:100])

# Add POS count feature name
feature_names_with_pos = list(tfidf_vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()) + ['pos_count']

# Summary Plot
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_test[:100], feature_names=feature_names_with_pos)

Advanced Modeling (DistilBERT)¶

A deep contextual language model is then trained to classify sentiment based on semantic and syntactic patterns. Transformer models (like BERT) can understand context and word meaning better than traditional approaches. DistilBERT was used as a lightweight variant to BERT as it performs well with fewer resources and fine-tuning is simplified through Hugging Face.

In [8]:
from transformers import DistilBertTokenizerFast, DistilBertForSequenceClassification, Trainer, TrainingArguments
from datasets import Dataset

# Split raw reviews and labels for fine-tuning
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
train_texts, test_texts, train_labels, test_labels = train_test_split(df['review'].tolist(), df['label'].tolist(), test_size=0.2)

# Tokenize
tokenizer = DistilBertTokenizerFast.from_pretrained('distilbert-base-uncased')
train_encodings = tokenizer(train_texts, truncation=True, padding=True)
test_encodings = tokenizer(test_texts, truncation=True, padding=True)

# Convert to Hugging Face Dataset
train_dataset = Dataset.from_dict({**train_encodings, 'label': train_labels})
test_dataset = Dataset.from_dict({**test_encodings, 'label': test_labels})

# Load model
model = DistilBertForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained("distilbert-base-uncased", num_labels=2)

# Define training params
training_args = TrainingArguments(
    output_dir="./results",
    eval_strategy="epoch",
    save_strategy="epoch",  # Added to match eval_strategy
    learning_rate=2e-5,
    per_device_train_batch_size=32,
    per_device_eval_batch_size=64, # Corrected typo
    num_train_epochs=3,
    weight_decay=0.01,
    logging_dir="./logs",
    logging_steps=50,  # Added back
    save_total_limit=2,  # Added back
    load_best_model_at_end=True, # Added back
    fp16=True # Added back
)

# Train
trainer = Trainer(
    model=model,
    args=training_args,
    train_dataset=train_dataset,
    eval_dataset=test_dataset
)

trainer.train()

KEY INSIGHTS AND RECOMMENDATIONS¶

  • Key findings summary
  • Recommendations for future iterations of this project
  • Recommendations for the Data Visualizer team member

Key Findings Summary¶

Performance Benchmarks

  1. Logistic Regression (LR) achieved excellent accuracy (89%) and AUC (0.96), indicating it's highly effective for high-dimensional sparse text (TF-IDF).
  2. Random Forest (RF) was outperformed by LR with lower accuracy (84%) and AUC (0.92), suggesting RF may be suboptimal for TF-IDF style sparse matrices without feature selection or dimensionality reduction.
  3. DistilBERT provided the best raw classification performance (lowest FP/FN count, ~91% accuracy), demonstrating that transformer-based models capture deeper semantic context beyond lexical features.

Model Interpretability

  1. SHAP values for LR and RF clearly highlighted interpretable sentiment indicators (i.e., "bad", "great", "love"), affirming model transparency.
  2. DistilBERT lacks native SHAP interpretability out-of-the-box, suggesting future work is needed for explainability (i.e., using Captum or another solution).

EDA Insights

  1. Word clouds validated model understanding by highlighting emotionally polarized words in positive/negative reviews.
  2. Common terms like "film" and "movie" appears in both classes, supporting the need for contextual models like DistilBERT to resolve ambiguity.

Recommendations for Future Project Iterations¶

  1. Integrate explainability for DistilBERT to expose how BERT variants arrive at predictions and uncover semantic patterns.
  2. Explore domain adaptation for fine-tuning (i.e., Rotten Tomatoes, YouTube comments) to improve accuracy, generalization, and context-awareness.
  3. Incorporate additional metadata features to test if hybrid models (structured + unstructured) yield stronger results.
  4. Try dimensionality reduction for tree-based models as it could potentially improve tree model performance and reduce runtime.
  5. Deploy and monitor with live data for model drift detection.

Recommendations for Data Visualizer¶

  1. Unify ROC, Confusion Matrix, and SHAP for All Models into a Dashboard
    • Create a side-by-side visual comparison of model performance using Plotly, Dash, Altair, or Matplotlib Subplots to support stakeholder model selection.
  2. Build an Interactive SHAP Explorer

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Calculate the review length and add it to the DataFrame
df['review_length'] = df['review'].apply(len)

# Create a figure with 6 subplots (2 rows, 3 columns)
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 8))

# Plot 1: Sentiment Distribution (Original)
plt.subplot(2, 3, 1)
df['sentiment'].value_counts().plot(kind='bar', color=['lightcoral', 'lightgreen'])
plt.title('Sentiment Distribution')
plt.xlabel('Sentiment')
plt.ylabel('Count')

# Plot 2: Distribution of POS tags (Original)
plt.subplot(2, 3, 2)
sns.histplot(data=df, x='pos_count', hue='sentiment', multiple="stack")
plt.title('Distribution of Adjectives/Adverbs')
plt.xlabel('Number of Adjectives/Adverbs')
plt.ylabel('Count')

# Plot 3: Review Length by Sentiment (Original)
plt.subplot(2, 3, 3)
sns.boxplot(data=df, x='sentiment', y='review_length')
plt.title('Review Length by Sentiment')
plt.xlabel('Sentiment')
plt.ylabel('Review Length')

# Plot 4: Review Length Distribution
plt.subplot(2, 3, 4)
sns.histplot(data=df, x='review_length', hue='sentiment', multiple="stack", bins=50)
plt.title('Review Length Distribution by Sentiment')
plt.xlabel('Review Length')
plt.ylabel('Count')

# Plot 5: POS Count vs Review Length
plt.subplot(2, 3, 5)
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='review_length', y='pos_count', hue='sentiment', alpha=0.5)
plt.title('POS Count vs Review Length')
plt.xlabel('Review Length')
plt.ylabel('Number of Adjectives/Adverbs')

# Plot 6: Average POS Count by Sentiment
plt.subplot(2, 3, 6)
sns.barplot(data=df, x='sentiment', y='pos_count', errorbar=('ci', 95))
plt.title('Average POS Count by Sentiment')
plt.xlabel('Sentiment')
plt.ylabel('Average Number of Adjectives/Adverbs')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

COMPREHENSIVE INSIGHTS¶

  1. Sentiment Distribution

    • Shows nearly balanced distribution between positive and negative reviews
    • Demonstrates dataset is well-balanced for training

  2. Distribution of Adjectives/Adverbs (POS Tags)

    • Stacked histogram showing frequency of descriptive words by sentiment
    • Reveals how sentiment correlates with use of descriptive language
    • Most reviews contain 5-15 adjectives/adverbs

  3. Review Length by Sentiment

    • Box plots comparing length distribution between sentiments
    • Shows median length and outliers for each sentiment class
    • Positive and negative reviews have similar length distributions

  4. Review Length Distribution

    • Stacked histogram showing review length frequency by sentiment
    • Most reviews fall between 100-500 words
    • Long tail indicates presence of very detailed reviews

  5. POS Count vs Review Length

    • Scatter plot showing relationship between review length and descriptive words
    • Positive correlation between length and adjective/adverb usage
    • Distinct clustering patterns for each sentiment

  6. Average POS Count by Sentiment

    • Bar plot comparing mean adjective/adverb usage between sentiments
    • Error bars show 95% confidence intervals
    • Slight difference in descriptive language use between sentiments
